TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Interaction of Sex and Power Base on Perceptions of Managerial Effectiveness
AU  - Wiley, Mary Glenn
AU  - Eskilson, Arlene
Y1  - 1982/09/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256089
DO  - 10.5465/256089
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 671
EP  - 677
VL  - 25
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article presents information on a study which examined the interaction of sex and power base using a limited sample of managers. It reveals that characteristics associated with successful managers are more congruent with the traits attributed to men than to women. It also examines how the use of reward and expert power is related to sex-role stereotypes. It was hypothesized that the use of expert power by women would require sex-role inconsistent claims of expertise and competence. It discusses the limitations of the study. The research showed that similar strategies by men and women does not mean there will be an equivalent evaluation of their performance.
AB  - This article presents information on a study which examined the interaction of sex and power base using a limited sample of managers. It reveals that characteristics associated with successful managers are more congruent with the traits attributed to men than to women. It also examines how the use of reward and expert power is related to sex-role stereotypes. It was hypothesized that the use of expert power by women would require sex-role inconsistent claims of expertise and competence. It discusses the limitations of the study. The research showed that similar strategies by men and women does not mean there will be an equivalent evaluation of their performance.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256089
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256089
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

