TY  - JOUR
T1  - Institutional and Anti-Institutional Conflict among Business, Government, and the Public
AU  - Dowling, John B.
AU  - Schaefer, Norbert V.
Y1  - 1982/09/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256091
DO  - 10.5465/256091
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 683
EP  - 689
VL  - 25
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article presents information on a study which described the application of institutional and anti-institutional conflict in examining the changes in the relationship among business, government and the public at large. The two forms of conflict are institutional and anti-institutional. Two important considerations dominate the nature of the business-government relationship. It examines informed business journalism on the role of government and public opinion attitudes toward both business and government. The authors draw the conclusion that the results prove that conflict between business and government in the United States has lessened significantly.
AB  - This article presents information on a study which described the application of institutional and anti-institutional conflict in examining the changes in the relationship among business, government and the public at large. The two forms of conflict are institutional and anti-institutional. Two important considerations dominate the nature of the business-government relationship. It examines informed business journalism on the role of government and public opinion attitudes toward both business and government. The authors draw the conclusion that the results prove that conflict between business and government in the United States has lessened significantly.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256091
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256091
Y2  - 2026/04/24
